Has there been a polarization of working hours? Analysis of the European Union Labor Force Survey

Problematic and motivations

Both academic and public debates suggest that there has been a polarization of working hours. Some people are working very short hoursthe underemployed, and some work very long hoursthe overworked. Further, longer hours are concentrated among those with higher earnings and shorter hours among those with low earnings. Such a polarization has important consequences, not just for social inequality overall, but also for the lives of the individual workers.

But is this actually true? This StatApp will investigate this question by analyzing long-running survey data to assess trends in working hours across European countries. We will make use of unconditional quantile regression and Oaxaca-Blinder decompositions. These models enable us to understand, which group, like single-mothers or physicians, contribute to changes in the working hour distribution over time.

  group_by(country) %>%
  summarise(mean_hwactual = mean(hwactual, na.rm = TRUE))

# Create a horizontal bar plot

  geom_col(width = 0.7) +

Figure 6. People whose working hours are significantly far from the mean have different preferences compared with average workers. Density of the number of hours wish to work: in black for all workers combined, in red for people who usually work less than 30 hours in their main job and in blue for people who work more than 50 hours in their main job, all years combined. 31 countries from the 2014 release of the EU Labor Force Survey, own analyses.

We may conclude by saying that workers face constraints that lead them to choose more (respectively less) hours than the average, apart from the number of hours they are offered. For instance, looking on children or on the elderly may partly explain the fact that people who work less than 30 hours in main job almost never want to work more than 40.

Figure 7. Median weekly working hours are stable over time and across countries contrary to top and bottom deciles. A few order statistics: the bottom decile, the median and the top decile of the number of hours usually worked in main job. 30 countries from the 2014 release of the EU Labor Force Survey, own analyses.

For each country, the situation stays somewhat stable over time, with a few exceptions: strong variation concerning the bottom decile in Hungary in particular and in other countries to a smaller extent. However, the situation varies a lot across countries. In some parts of Europe (Hungary, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Norway, Sweden), the top decile is at the same level as the median. In other parts of Europe (Bulgaria, Czech Republic, Slovak Republic), on the contrary, the bottom decile is at the same level as the median. We may also notice that the bottom decile is much more variable than the top one, across countries and over time. We do not see any significant effect of the 2008 crisis. The Netherlands are an exception since its median is slightly decreasing, or at least more variable than any other median. Romania and Lithuania are particular cases: both have a very low bottom decile.

We seem to have a problem with Romania: top and bottom deciles are much more stable than in other countries.

# Starting by creating a smaller base to work with
eulfs_RO <- eulfs_small %>% filter(country == 27) %>% select(hwusual, refyear)
# Indicating what statistics we want to appear on the plot
frame <- eulfs_RO %>% group_by(refyear, .drop = NA) %>% summarise(Min = min(hwusual, na.rm = TRUE), Max = max(hwusual, na.rm = TRUE), Median = median(hwusual, na.rm = TRUE), quant1 = quantile(hwusual, probs = 0.25, na.rm = TRUE), quant2 = quantile(hwusual, probs = 0.75, na.rm = TRUE), dec1 = quantile(hwusual, probs = 0.10, na.rm = TRUE), dec9 = quantile(hwusual, probs = 0.90, na.rm = TRUE), dec05 = quantile(hwusual, probs = 0.05, na.rm = TRUE), dec95 = quantile(hwusual, probs = 0.95, na.rm = TRUE))

# Get the density estimate
dens1 <- density(eulfs_RO$hwusual, na.rm = TRUE)
# Need to delete negative values for the number of working hours, as well as the values above 80 hours which are absent to the dataset
# Need for x and y with the same length
n <- length(dens1[[1]])
dens1[[1]] <- dens1[[1]][!(dens1[[1]] < 0)]
n_1 <- length(dens1[[1]])
loss_1 <- n - n_1 # number of first elements that were deleted
dens1[[1]] <- dens1[[1]][!(dens1[[1]] > 80)]
loss_2 <- n_1 - length(dens1[[1]]) # number of last elements that were deleted
dens1[[2]] <- tail(dens1[[2]],-loss_1)
dens1[[2]] <- head(dens1[[2]], -loss_2)

##### Plot -------
# Plot y-values scaled by number of observations against x values
par(mar = c(5.1, 5.1, 4.1, 2.1))

Figure 9. On average, Romanians work as much as other Europeans, but a very strong minority does not work. Density of the number of hours usually worked in Romania. From the 2014 release of the EU Labor Force Survey, own analyses.

One explanation is the high rate of emigration: one person finds work in another country and becomes the bread-winner of a whole family. For instance, a couple made up of a male immigrant and a housewife.

We may analyse data for an other specific country, for instance Austria.
